	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hey.<br><br>For someone who has so many rants, you seem to have slipped into a little bit of naivity here:<br><i>He did commercials served food at Wendy’s and made the company feel like it was home spun.</i><br>That's <b>image</b>!&nbsp;&nbsp;It's not real!  How many burgers do you supose he served, when there wasn't a camera on him?  (You have to cut me a little slack at this point.  I'm not American, so I'm not entirely au fait with Wendy's.  I have a feeling they specialise in chicken and not burgers.  But, either way, I'm sure you understand my point.)<br><br><i>Dave was rare in today’s corporate world, someone only rivaled by Cornel Sanders of KFC or Bill Gates.</i><br>I don't know how old you are, so I'm gonna make a guess here.  I'd be inclined to guess you're in your early twenties, or maybe a little younger.  Colonel Sanders died around 1981.  (I'm not sure of the exact year, off the top of my head.)  But, this means that, if my guess about your age is close, you <b>don't</b> remember colonel Sanders.  What you associate with KFC is an image of a Southern gentleman, with a wuite suit.  (Which <b>was</b> an appropriate description of Colonel Sanders.  <b>But</b>, it's not actually the man himself you're making an association with.  <br><br>It's marketing image.  (It's really no different to Ronald McDonald!)  Someone decides that Wendy's should be homely, so Dave throws a coupla burgers on the grill in front of the camera.  Someone decides that KFC should be associated with a guy from Kentucky, so they use a cartoon of a Southern gent.  It's not real.  None of it.<br><br>Bill Gates is reviled by thousands, if not millions.  For no particular reason, other than because he's successful!  There are thousands of computer geeks who use Linux, purely because it's not made by Microsoft.  (Linux has it's plus points, but frankly, for the casual user, it's a poor second, to MS Windows.)  <br>He stepped down as CEO of Microsoft, as a sacrificial lamb, during the court action against Microsoft.  But, frankly, if he expressed the opinion that he hates the public, who could blame him after the grief he has been on the receiving end of?<br><br><i>The only really successful businessman I can think of, who's genuinely popular, is Richard Branson.  (He's English, so I don't know how well known he is un the US.)</i><br><br>In general, to be successful, requires hardness and the ability to make unpopular decisions.  And this doesn't lead to popularity.  Therefore, the head of a company is not going to be popular.  And it's far more efficient, to let the company's image to be built by style analysts.<br><br>That's all you have anywhere.  Where it seems that the CEO is part of a nice cosy image, it's just a fake anyway!<br><br>Anyhow, it looks like it's my turn to be cynical, while you're not.  That's basically all I have to say.<br><br>See ya in Norrath.<br><br>AlAaraaf.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></tr>
