	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have switched over to AO. This week is the explanation why.<br>Introduction:<br>AO and DAOC are foils for each other. AO had a bad launch; DAOC had a good launch. Now the roles are reversed DAOC is the unfinished game and AO is better. “What did you say? AO is ‘better than DAOC’. You’re a &amp;*_$&amp;_$&amp;_ and get off this site you P.O.S!!!” Yep, I said that and in my opinion, it’s true. DAOC is unfinished unbalanced and in the end is EQ in a Camelot world. One could say that AO is EQ in the future. In some ways it is, but has enough distinctions to make it unique.&nbsp;&nbsp;The purpose of the following is to explain why that is and why I am now an AO addict as opposed to a Daoc addict.<br><br>Part One: The most amazing unfinished, cookie cutter game ever.  <br>DAOC was a dream. A dream that looked good in the begging but ended up being average. The promises were huge. “a massive world” and “great RVR”. Yes the hype for DAOC was huge. It was billed as the EQ killer and it was poised to be. But there was one problem it was slightly rushed. No, it was really rushed. While the low levels are magnificent, the high level game sucked, and classes were heavily unbalanced or so I was told. <br>See I never got past level 10 with either of my 2 characters I played, but that was not. The problem is that I had no motivation to do so because DAOC is EQ. It is in the same type of environment and has similar classes(AO borrows some but ill get to that soon). I found that I was doing the exact same things I did in EQ; camping, having to group ect. I asked myself, why should I log on?  Sure I could RVR once I got to 30, but who wants to wait that long for something that I probably will still be too low to anyway. So what will I be left with when I get up there, same old EQ in a different package?  While I believe that mythic plans to make the game better and different (see last rant), I have no motivation to play it and don’t really care to wait that long. I am keeping my account active so that when mythic makes the game better, I will be there to play it. I still am holding on to that dream of greatness; and while I think mythic can fulfill it, its not there yet.<br><br>Part two: Why AO  will own you.<br><br>AO is the most unfairly trashed game ever. Just because it had a bad launch (understatement), does not mean it’s a bad game. In fact it is one of the best game ever. Its not just because of the graphics and atmosphere (which helps), it’s the overall package that hooked me and is not letting go. AO’s initial problems were mainly technical; lag crashes bugs and some of its still there.  But beneath those bugs lays a game that it simply wonderful. It is for a few reasons. One, it caters to the hardcore as well as the casual gamer. If you not cannot get a get group and go hunt somewhere, go run solo missions. In fact I have mostly soloed most of the time I have been playing it. However, there are plenty of group activities too, including, dungeons, PVP and team missions. And that’s not all. You also get cool little things like cars, your own apartment, bathing suits and strip clubs (there is even a red-light district in Omni-1 entertainment). <br>Frankly, the change of setting and the ideas that come with it are cool too. The teleport system is handled trough a grid that you can teleport from the place to place instantly (no more druids). You get implants that add stat buffs on top of the clothes and weapons you wear. Not only that, you can now save (you only lose exp that you gained since the last time you saved) and get your stuff back instantly in insurance reclaim. Plus, no more reliance on healers because anyone can heal with first aid kids and no more waiting for your “mana”(nanos in this game) to recharge because of nano refreshers.<br><br>However, I must mention some of the negatives in this game. There is still forced grouping in high levels when soloing becomes less profitable. There is also a somewhat bloated economy, but everything has stat requirements so it helps a little. Also sometimes the game can feel depressing because of the environments. Finally its still a leveling treadmill like EQ and DAOC but I don’t really mind all that much because its not as monotonous as the other two.  But even with its faults, I recommend it, but its not for everyone. So next time before you trash it, think about playing some of it before you do.<br><br>Part 3: Off topic on Luclin graphics.<br>I am sorry, but the character graphics the came with Luclin suck hardcore. Everyone now looks worse and somewhat similar, I cannot tell the difference between a wood elf and humans except for what they are wearing. The females (wood-elves especially) look like men except for the even larger bust lines. Hell, they even put little breasts on the Iksar females; come-on Verant, lizards don’t breast-feed their young. Don’t even get me started on the barbarians, dark-elves and Erudites. My halfling druid dad, used to look cute, now looks ugly (understatement). I shudder to think what Lakanar and Roshi would have looked like. I think Luclin was rushed so fast they forgot how to make good character graphics. Its not like the old ones were great, but they didn’t hurt my eyes to look at them. Good god, Verant took a game whose graphics were ok and made them worse, shame on them. AO and DAOC look like renaissance masterpieces in comparison. If you think I am pulling this out of my butt, I saw them, for real; REALLY I DID.<br><br>Also, is it just me, or every expansion Frionia Vie gets sexier. I bet for the next release, she will be wearing a thong and bikini top so small it will barely hide her nipples.<br>Roshi out.<br><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
